<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>HTML Basics Tutorial</title>
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>Welcome to the HTML Basics Tutorial</h1>
    </header>

    <section>
        <h2>Introduction to HTML</h2>
        <p>HTML (Hypertext Markup Language) is the standard language for creating web pages. It defines the structure and content of a web page using various elements and tags.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Basic HTML Structure</h2>
        <p>Every HTML document consists of the following basic structure:</p>
        <pre>
            &lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
            &lt;html lang="en"&gt;
            &lt;head&gt;
                &lt;meta charset="UTF-8"&gt;
                &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"&gt;
                &lt;title&gt;Page Title&lt;/title&gt;
            &lt;/head&gt;
            &lt;body&gt;
                &lt;!-- Content Goes Here --&gt;
            &lt;/body&gt;
            &lt;/html&gt;
        </pre>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>HTML Elements and Tags</h2>
        <p>HTML uses various elements and tags to define the content and structure of a web page. Here are some commonly used ones:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> to <code>&lt;h6&gt;</code>: Headings</li>
            <li><code>&lt;p&gt;</code>: Paragraphs</li>
            <li><code>&lt;a&gt;</code>: Hyperlinks</li>
            <li><code>&lt;img&gt;</code>: Images</li>
            <li><code>&lt;ul&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code>: Unordered and Ordered Lists</li>
            <li><code>&lt;li&gt;</code>: List Items</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>HTML Attributes</h2>
        <p>HTML elements can have attributes that provide additional information. For example:</p>
        <pre>
            &lt;a href="https://www.example.com"&gt;Visit Example&lt;/a&gt;
            &lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="Description"&gt;
        </pre>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Creating Your First HTML Page</h2>
        <p>To create your first HTML page, follow these steps:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Create a new text file with the <code>.html</code> extension (e.g., <code>index.html</code>).</li>
            <li>Edit the file using a text editor.</li>
            <li>Add the basic HTML structure as shown earlier.</li>
            <li>Add content within the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> element.</li>
            <li>Save the file.</li>
            <li>Open it in a web browser to view your HTML page.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h2>Conclusion</h2>
        <p>Congratulations! You've just completed a basic HTML tutorial. HTML is the foundation of web development, and this tutorial is just the beginning of your journey. Explore more HTML elements and attributes to create rich and interactive web pages.</p>
    </section>

    <footer>
        <p>For more advanced HTML and web development topics, consider exploring further resources and tutorials.</p>
    </footer>
</body>
</html>
